<TITLE> Key steps to form a new Indian government </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 India, Mon May 11, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A five-stage polling process to elect India's new government ends with the last phase of voting on May 13. Here are details of what could unfold in the next few weeks, leading to the formation of the next government. May 13-15 Television channels (NDTV, CNN-IBN, STAR News among others) will broadcast exit polls from May 13 to May 15, based on sample surveys of voters in major Indian cities. The polls, which have had a mixed record in the past, will project the winner of the election, or a coalition which could form the country's next government. May 16 Counting of votes gets under way and a clear picture of whether the ruling Congress or the main opposition Bharatiya Janata Party will be the single-largest party is expected by late afternoon. May 16-17 In case of a hung parliament, as seems likely, political parties start meeting allies and send feelers to regional parties to cobble together 272 members to form a coalition government from the 543-member lower house of parliament. May 17 onwards Prime Minister Manmohan Singh formally submits his resignation to President Pratibha Patil following the conclusion of the vote count. The president will however ask Singh to continue as caretaker prime minister until a new government is ready to take charge. The president is expected to invite the party which emerges as the single largest group in the new parliament to try to form a government. Once the party has the support of 272 members, it will go back to Patil to submit the list. The Election Commission has said a new government must be formed by June 2, after the deadline for the present government's tenure ends on June 1. By June 15 The new government will have to prove its majority in parliament within a specified period of time, possibly by around June 15. The government prepares to present its first budget by Jun
